04739nam a22007695i 9780812205244DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20112012pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)883803763  a97808122052447 a10.9783/97808122052442doi  a(DE-B1597)449399  a(OCoLC)793012722  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aPT2621.A26bZ8946 2012eb 7aLIT0041702bisacsh04a833 .9122231 aSuchoff, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aKafka's Jewish Languages :bThe Hidden Openness of Tradition /cDavid Suchoff. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2011] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHaney Foundation Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction. Kafka’s Jewish Voice -- tChapter 1. Cold War Kafka and Beyond -- tChapter 2. The Breakthrough to Jewish Languages -- tChapter 3. Hebrews in New York -- tChapter 4. Kabbalah and Comedy -- tChapter 5. Open Boundaries -- tAfterword. The Puzzle of National Traditions, or the Art of Nut-Cracking -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAfter Franz Kafka died in 1924, his novels and short stories were published in ways that downplayed both their author's roots in Prague and his engagement with Jewish tradition and language, so as to secure their place in the German literary canon. Now, nearly a century after Kafka began to create his fictions, Germany, Israel, and the Czech Republic lay claim to his legacy. Kafka's Jewish Languages brings Kafka's stature as a specifically Jewish writer into focus.David Suchoff explores the Yiddish and modern Hebrew that inspired Kafka's vision of tradition. Citing the Jewish sources crucial to the development of Kafka's style, the book demonstrates the intimate relationship between the author's Jewish modes of expression and the larger literary significance of his works. Suchoff shows how "The Judgment" evokes Yiddish as a language of comic curse and examines how Yiddish, African American, and culturally Zionist voices appear in the unfinished novel, Amerika. In his reading of The Trial, Suchoff highlights the black humor Kafka learned from the Yiddish theater, and he interprets The Castle in light of Kafka's involvement with the renewal of the Hebrew language. Finally, he uncovers the Yiddish and Hebrew meanings behind Kafka's "Josephine the Singer, or the Mouse-Folk" and considers the recent legal case in Tel Aviv over the possession of Kafka's missing manuscripts as a parable of the transnational meanings of his writing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aElectronic books. 4aJewish Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aJewish Studies.  aLiterature.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook-Package Literaturez978311041354008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220524440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812205244423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812205244.jpg  a978-3-11-041345-8  Penn Press eBook Package Complete Collection  a978-3-11-041354-0  Penn Press eBook-Package Literature  a978-3-11-045954-8  University of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK